  "prompt": "If light is energy why doesn't it have mass?",
  "response": "Actually, this is a common misconception. Light (photons) does have mass in a sense, but it's a bit more complicated:\n\n1. Rest Mass:\n- Photons have zero rest mass, meaning when not moving\n- This is different from having no mass at all\n\n2. Relativistic Mass:\n- When photons are moving (which is always), they have energy\n- According to Einstein's E=mc\u00b2, energy and mass are equivalent\n- So moving photons do exhibit a form of mass related to their energy\n\n3. Key Points:\n- Photons have no rest mass\n- They have momentum and energy\n- They can interact with matter and be affected by gravity\n- Their \"mass\" is expressed through their energy when in motion\n\n4. Scientific Explanation:\n- Photons are massless particles at rest\n- But they carry energy and momentum\n- They behave differently from matter with rest mass\n- They always move at the speed of light\n\n5. Quantum Mechanics:\n- Photons are considered both particles and waves\n- Their mass-like properties emerge through their energy and interactions\n\nSo while photons don't have traditional mass, they do have mass-equivalent properties through their energy and momentum.",
